Claddagh ring</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>Claddagh ring</b> (<a href="/wiki/Irish_language" title="Irish language">Irish</a>: <span lang="gle" xml:lang="gle"><i>f√°inne Chladach</i></span>) is a <a href="/wiki/Traditional" title="Traditional" class="mw-redirect">traditional</a> <a href="/wiki/Ireland" title="Ireland">Irish</a> ring given in <a href="/wiki/Friendship_ring" title="Friendship ring" class="mw-redirect">friendship</a> or worn as a <a href="/wiki/Wedding_ring" title="Wedding ring">wedding ring</a>. The design and customs associated with it originated in the Irish fishing village of <a href="/wiki/Claddagh" title="Claddagh">Claddagh</a>, located just outside the old walls of the city of <a href="/wiki/Galway" title="Galway">Galway</a>. The ring was first produced in the 17th century during the reign of Queen <a href="/wiki/Mary_II_of_England" title="Mary II of England">Mary II</a>, though elements of the design are much older.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
